Disk Forensics > [T5]: Monitoring Low-Level Changes in NTFS

(3) $LogFile

NTFS uses $LogFile to monitor the changes to files/folders, but unlike $Usnjrnl, it stores detailed low-level changes to provide more resilience to the file system. Since it holds more low-level details, it usually stores changes for past hours or maybe a day in the best cases. Like $MFT, the $LogFile is located in the volume root.

 

$Logfile location - (zoom in)

  1. Volume root
  2. $Logfile

Unfortunately, "MFTEcmd" cannot parse $LogFile at the time of writing this lesson. However, another cool tool called "NTFS Log Tracker" can parse $LogFile. Not only that, It analyzes the three $Logfile, $usnjrnl, and $MFT in a single interface.

 

NTFS Log tracker - (zoom in)

  1. $Logfile tab
  2. Event timestamp.
  3. Event type.
  4. File or directory name.
  5. Object full path (location).
  6. Creation time.
  7. Modification time.
  8. The number of records in $Logfile. As you can see, $UsnJrn has a more considerable number of logs (because it tracks changes for a longer time) compared to $LogFile. 

One of the "NTFS log tracker" cool features is "Suspicious behaviors detection." As you can see in the following view, it identified the usage of CCleaner to wipe attack traces.

 

Suspicious behaviors detection - (zoom in)

  1. Suspicious behavior categories.
  2. Detection details window. The tool identified the execution of "CCleaner."
  3. The source log file was used to identify the suspicious behavior. The tool identified the execution of CCleaner from a prefetch file (will be explained later).
